<TITLE> C'wealth Youth meet begins </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May (bdnews24.com)  The regional mid-term review meeting of the Commonwealth Youth Programme for Asia got underway in Dhaka on Monday. State minister for youth and sports Md Ahad Ali Sarker inaugurated the two-day meeting, participated by delegations from eight countries, at Dhaka Sheraton hotel. The state minister said a comprehensive plan was needed to make the commonwealth youth development programmes in Asia more active. He said Bangladesh has launched the national service programme, a public-private partnership scheme intended for ensuring employment of educated but poor youths. "A timely national youth policy has been adopted and different programmes are being implemented under the programme," he said. Sri Lankan deputy minister for youth affairs Mahindananda Aluthgamage, youth affairs department director of Commonwealth Secretariat Dr Fatiha Serawar and Asia region director of Commonwealth Youth Programme Raj K Mishra also spoke. During the meeting the delegations will prepare a set of recommendations, to be presented in the next minister-level meeting, for development of the youth. The countries participating in the meeting apart from host Bangladesh are Brunei Darussalam, India, Malaysia, Maldives, Pakistan, Sri Lanka and Singapore
